  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Comics of the New Europe,\" published by Leuven University Press in 2023, is poised to influence both academic and public discussions surrounding the evolving landscape of comics in Europe. Although the current metrics do not showcase online mentions or citations, the book's substantive approach to the medium suggests potential for future engagement and exploration within scholarly and community frameworks.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">\"Comics of the New Europe\" contributes to the growing discourse on the intersection of comics and cultural representation in contemporary European contexts. As a publication from Leuven University Press, it carries institutional credibility, signaling a serious academic investment in the subject matter. The absence of citations and online mentions at this point may reflect the recency of publication, but it does not diminish the book's potential relevance in both scholarly circles and popular media discussions.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The narratives embedded within the book are expected to resonate with various audiences interested in European art forms. By focusing on comics, the work opens pathways for interdisciplinary engagement, appealing not only to scholars of literature and art but also to those in cultural studies and history. Its insightful analysis could foster discussion in classrooms, workshops, and conferences alike, setting the stage for academic exploration and public discourse.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">While the immediate online presence is absent, the commercial linkage observed through platforms like Amazon and Goodreads indicates a readiness for wider consumption and recognition. This suggests that readers are beginning to find value in the themes and arguments presented, potentially leading to grassroots discussions in the future.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, \"Comics of the New Europe\" stands as a timely contribution to its field, reflecting ongoing transformations in Eastern and Western European comics. The work\u2019s impact will likely unfold over time, gradually shaping both academic conversations and public perceptions about the role of comics in cultural dialogue across Europe.</p>",
